#open-question(title: [Does Interoceptive Accuracy-Sensibility Dissociation Predict ME/CFS Chronicity in Post-Infectious Cohorts?])[
Long COVID provides a natural experiment: a large, precipitated-onset cohort with known timing of the initial immune insult. A longitudinal study (n=200 post-COVID) measuring HBDT, MAIA, TAS-20, and cytokines at 3, 6, 12, and 24 months post-infection would test whether interoceptive accuracy-sensibility dissociation at 3 months predicts transition to ME/CFS diagnostic criteria at 12 months (predicted AUC > 0.70). If validated, it would provide the first prospective biomarker of post-infectious ME/CFS development and would test the Garfinkel dissociation as a mechanistic predictor, not just a concurrent correlate. The MS literature provides a cross-disease template: Danciut, Garfinkel et al.\ (2024) found interoceptive accuracy deficits linked to fatigue in MS via white matter dysconnectivity @DanciutGarfinkel2024MSinteroception — the same relationship should hold in post-infectious ME/CFS but with the additional temporal dimension that the acute trigger's timing is known. (Origin: brainstorm)
